19th
A function can also be referred as a method or a sub-routine or a procedure, etc. 
  -this statement means the required function is predefined by the user so that it tells the compiler how to perform the particular task 
  
In such case, you should declare the function at the top of the file calling the function.
 - this means if we want to use a function in the program then we should write the source code before hand so that the compiler 
 understands what to do.
 
 after defining a function or writring a source code for a function we need to 
 call that function to our program to perform the specific operation.
 
 so how to call a function after defining it ?
 To call a function, you simply need to pass the required parameters along with the function name, and if the
 function returns a value, then you can store the returned value.
 
what happens after calling a function? 
-When a program calls a function, the program control is transferred to the called function.
    A called function performs a defined task and when its return statement is executed or when
    its function-ending closing brace is reached, it returns the program control back to the main program.
   
 So the example for the whole thing is 
 #include <stdio.h>
 
/* function declaration */
int max(int num1, int num2);-here int is the return type ,max is the name of the function and int num1 ,int num2 are the parameters
 
int main () {

   /* local variable definition */
   int a = 100;
   int b = 200;
   int ret;
 
   /* calling a function to get max value */
   ret = max(a, b);
 
   printf( "Max value is : %d\n", ret );
 
   return 0;
}
the function which is to be called the above program is 
/* function returning the max between two numbers */
int max(int num1, int num2) {

   /* local variable declaration */
   int result;
 
   if (num1 > num2)
      result = num1;
   else
      result = num2;
 
   return result; 
}

